  "opinion": "As a man in my sixties who's been a barista for decades in Philadelphia, I've seen how science gets misunderstood by folks who don't understand its roots. The gender gap in science isn't just about women being underrepresented—it's about how society frames who can even think scientifically. My wife, a teacher, often tells me that when kids start school, they're taught to see science as a 'boy's thing,' and that's why so many girls lose interest early. I've never been a scientist myself, but I know that when I'm at work, people often ask me why I don't do more with my photography—because I'm not 'technical enough.' That's the real issue: people don't realize that science isn't just about lab coats and equations; it's about curiosity and observation, which anyone can have. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big lectures or programs that assume everyone has the same background. For me, it's about creating spaces where people feel they belong, like when I take my kids to the park and we look at the stars together. That's science without the jargon. And how? By starting small—like helping neighbors with their gardening projects or teaching kids how to build simple models. It's not about fixing what's broken but helping people see that science is part of their everyday life. After all, my father was a PhD and my mother taught in a school, but I never felt like I had the 'right' background to be in science. So, let's stop pretending that science is only for certain people and start seeing it as something that belongs to everyone, starting with the people who already care about it.",
